Today I want to show you the future of the way we make things.
I believe that soon our buildings and machines will be able to self-assemble, self-replicate and self-repair.
So I want to show you what I think manufacturing is today, and then I want to compare it to some natural systems.
So in current manufacturing, we have skyscrapers -- two and a half years, half a million to a million parts, very complex, using new technologies in steel, concrete and glass.
We have exciting machines that can take us into space -- five years, two and a half million parts.
But on the other hand, if you look at natural systems, we have two million types of proteins that can fold in 10,000 nanoseconds, and we can replicate DNA with three billion base pairs in about an hour.
That's the complexity of our natural systems, but they're very efficient, more efficient than anything we've built, more complex than anything we can build.
They're more efficient in terms of energy.
They rarely make mistakes.
They can repair themselves to maintain longevity.
There's a super interesting thing about natural systems.
If we can translate that into our built environment, there's a lot of potential in the way we build things.
I think the key is self-assembly.
If we want to use self-assembly in our own physical environment, I think there are four key elements.
The first is that we need to decode all the complexity of what we're building -- that is, our buildings and our machines.
We need to decode them into simple sequences -- basically the DNA that makes our buildings work.
Then we need programmable parts of the part that can accept that sequence and use it to fold or reshape.
We need some energy to activate it, so that we can program these parts to fold up.
We need some type of error correction redundancy to make sure that we succeed in building exactly what we want.
So I want to show you some of the projects that my colleagues and I are working on to make this self-assembling future a reality.
The first two projects are MacroBot and DeciBot.
These projects are massively reconfigurable robots -- 8-foot, 12-foot long proteins.
They're embedded with electromechanical devices, sensors.
You need to decode the way you want to fold into, decode into a series of angles -- negative 120 degrees, negative 120 degrees, 0 degrees, 0 degrees, 120 degrees, negative 120 degrees, -- that sort of thing; a series of angles, or steering, that can be wired to put that sequence passed through.
Each unit gets its own message -- say minus 120. It does a rotation, checks that it's in place and then passes the sequence on to its neighbors.
There are a lot of brilliant scientists, engineers, designers working on this project.
I think this project really reveals: is this really scalable?
I mean, it cost thousands of dollars and thousands of man-hours to build this eight-foot robot.
Can we really scale it up? Can we really embed robots in every part of it?
The next question is look at passivity, or passively trying to make the reconfiguration programmable.
But it goes a step further, it tries to do actual computation.
It basically embeds the basic building blocks of most computation, the digital logic gates, right into each part.
It's with and without gates.
Each gate that's going to be used for computation has a tetrahedron on it, and there are two input tetrahedrons.
One of them is the input from the user, just like you're building bricks.
The other one is the input from a brick that was placed before it came.
Then it gives the output in three dimensions.
This means that the user stacks the bricks in the way they want.
It does the calculations based on what it did before and your instructions.
Now it starts to move in 3-D space -- up or down.
Look on the left, the input of [1,1] equals 0 output, which means down.
On the right, [0,0] has an input of 1 output, which means up.
So what this really means is that our structure now contains the blueprint that we want to build.
So all the information about what we want to build is already embedded in it.
This means that we have some form of self-replication.
In this case, I call it self-directed replication, because you have the exact blueprint in your structure.
If you encounter an error, you can replace a part.
All the local information is embedded in it that tells you how to fix it.
So you have something that you can climb on, that reads it and outputs it one by one.
It's embedded directly; there's no external command input.
The last project that I'm going to show is called the eccentric chain, and it's probably the most exciting example of a passive self-assembly system that we're seeing right now.
It's reconfigurable and programmable, which makes it a completely passive system.
Basically you have a sequence of elements.
Each element is exactly the same, and they are eccentric.
Each chain, or each element, wants to turn to the right or to the left.
If you want to assemble the chain, you need to program it.
You have to tell each unit whether it wants to turn left or right.
When you shake the chain, it folds up and programs whatever structure you've coded for it -- so in this case, a spiral, in this case, two connected cubes.
Basically you can program in three dimensions -- or one dimension, two dimensions -- and the chain is completely passive.
What does this portend to us about the future?
I think it tells us about these possibilities for this self-assembly, self-replication, and self-repair in our physical structures, in our architecture, and in our machines.
There's new programmability in these parts.
From that you can get new possibilities for computation.
We will have spatial computing.
Imagine our buildings, our bridges, our machines, all the bricks that can do the actual computation.
What an amazing parallel and distributed computing capability and new design possibilities.
It's an exciting potential.
I think these projects that I'm showing you are just a small step into the future, if we realize these new technologies for a new self-assembling world.
Thank you.
