Recently, we've seen the impact of cyber attacks on the business world.
Data breaches at companies like JPMorgan, Yahoo, Home Depot and Target have resulted in hundreds of millions, if not billions, of dollars in losses.
A few more such attacks and the entire world economy would collapse.
The public sector is not immune.
From 2012 to 2014, the U.S. Office of Personnel Management suffered a very serious data breach.
Security clearance and fingerprint information was stolen, affecting 22 million employees.
You may have also heard that some government-sponsored hackers tried to use the stolen data to influence the outcome of elections in some countries.
Two recent examples are the massive data theft from the German Bundestag and the email theft from the Democratic National Committee.
Cyber threats have affected our democratic process.
And it's getting worse.
The more advanced computer technology becomes, the more vulnerable the means we have to protect our data.
In particular, a new computer technology called a quantum computer uses microscopic particles from nature to dramatically increase the computing power of computers.
It is so powerful that it can break many of the encryption systems we use today.
So are we hopeless?
Should we start packing up our electronic survival gear for the coming data apocalypse?
I don't think we're there yet.
Quantum computers are still in the lab and years away from practical use.
More importantly, there have been many major breakthroughs in the field of encryption.
For me, this is a very exciting time in the history of secure communications.
About 15 years ago, I learned that we had unlocked new skills to create quantum effects that don't exist in nature. I was very excited.
The idea of using the fundamental laws of physics to advance cryptography was very exciting to me.
Today, a select group of companies and labs, including mine, are taking this technology to the practical stage.
That's right.
We're going to use quanta to fight quanta.
How is this going to happen?
First, let's take a quick look at the world of encryption.
You need a briefcase, you have some important documents to send to your good friend, James Bond, to lock up and keep safe.
Because this material is top secret, we're going to use a super advanced briefcase.
It comes with a special combination lock, and once it's locked, it converts the contents of the file into random numbers.
So you just put the file in, lock it, and by that time the file has been converted to random numbers, and you send the briefcase to James.
While the briefcase is still in the mail, you call him and tell him the password.
Once he gets the briefcase, he enters the password, the file is deciphered, it's perfect, you've successfully delivered an encrypted message to James Bond.
(laughter) A fun example, but it illustrates the three main points of encryption.
The cipher - we call it the encryption key.
You can think of it as the password.
The phone call that told James the password.
We call this the secret key pass.
This ensures that we can deliver the secret key securely to the specified location.
And the lock that is used to encrypt and decrypt the file.
We call this the encryption algorithm.
With the secret key, it converts the contents of the file into a random number.
A good algorithm can do this, and without the secret key it is very difficult to break the code.
The importance of the algorithm is that if someone gets the briefcase and opens it, without the secret key, without knowing the encryption algorithm, they can't read the contents of the document.
All you get is some random numbers.
Most security systems rely on a secure secret key delivery method to get the secret key to the right place.
However, the rapid growth of computing power jeopardizes many of the secret key delivery methods we use today.
As an example, we now have a very widely used system, RSA.
When it was invented in 1977, it took about 4 trillion years to crack a 426-bit RSA key.
By 1994, only 17 years later, the code had been cracked.
As computers have become more powerful, the passwords we need have become longer and longer.
Nowadays, we often use 2048 or 4096-bit passwords.
As you can see, there is a battle going on between the encryptors and the decryptors, each trying to outwit the other.
In the next 10 to 15 years, the arrival of quantum computers will make it even faster to break the complex mathematical algorithms that underlie the cryptographic systems we use today.
In fact, quantum computers will turn our security castle into a house of cards that will collapse at the touch of a button.
We need to find ways to protect our castle.
In recent years, many research institutions have emerged to study how quantum effects can be used to enhance encryption.
There have been some exciting breakthroughs.
Remember the 3 key points of encryption? High quality secret keys, secure secret key delivery and very strong algorithms.
However, advances in science and engineering have jeopardized 2 of these priorities.
The first and foremost is the secret key.
Random numbers are the basis of secret keys.
But today, they are no longer truly random.
Currently, we generate secret keys based on random number frequencies, generated by software, which we call pseudo-random numbers.
The numbers generated by programs or mathematical methods always have some, perhaps not so obvious, patterns in them.
The lower the randomness, or in terminology, the lower the moisture content of these numbers, the more predictable they are.
Recently, some casinos were attacked in a very creative way.
They filmed the slot machines for a period of time and then analyzed them.
The cybercriminals used reverse engineering to create a pseudo-random number generator behind the reels.
This gives them a good chance of predicting the spin of the reels and making a lot of money.
The secret key is also insecure.
Having a true random number generator is important for generating secure passwords.
For several years, researchers have been trying to create true random number generators.
Most designs, however, are either not random enough, not fast enough, or difficult to reuse.
But the quantum world is truly random.
It is important to take advantage of this true randomness.
A device that can measure quantum effects can generate a continuous stream of random numbers very quickly.
The casino crime just described is no longer possible to stage.
